1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,691
Why do people fear other people?

2
00:00:02,801 --> 00:00:06,290
Why do many folks feel self-conscious around others?

3
00:00:06,480 --> 00:00:08,211
What's behind shyness?

4
00:00:08,321 --> 00:00:09,891
What can we do about it?

5
00:00:10,721 --> 00:00:15,331
Fear of other people is a big fear, but there is a way to conquer it.

6
00:00:15,601 --> 00:00:21,010
You can conquer fear of people if you will learn to put them into proper perspective.

7
00:00:21,681 --> 00:00:27,730
A business friend, who was doing exceptionally well operating his own wood novelty plant,

8
00:00:27,921 --> 00:00:31,411
explained to me how he got the proper perspective of people.

9
00:00:31,601 --> 00:00:33,490
This example is interesting.

10
00:00:34,081 --> 00:00:39,651
Before I went into the army in World War II, I was scared of just about everybody.

11
00:00:39,841 --> 00:00:43,331
You just wouldn't believe how shy and timid I was.

12
00:00:43,521 --> 00:00:46,050
I felt everyone else was a lot smarter.

13
00:00:46,240 --> 00:00:49,971
I worried about my physical and mental inadequacies.

14
00:00:50,240 --> 00:00:52,770
I thought I was born to fail.

15
00:00:53,281 --> 00:00:58,611
Then by some fortunate quirk of fate, I lost my fear of people in the army.

16
00:00:58,801 --> 00:01:05,651
During part of 1942 and 1943, when the Army was inducting men at a terrific clip,

17
00:01:05,760 --> 00:01:09,730
I was stationed as a medic at one of the big induction centers.

18
00:01:10,081 --> 00:01:13,651
Day after day, I assisted in examining those men.

19
00:01:13,921 --> 00:01:18,530
The more I looked at these recruits, the less afraid of people I became.

20
00:01:19,041 --> 00:01:24,611
All those men lined up by the hundreds, naked as jaybirds, looked so much alike.

21
00:01:24,881 --> 00:01:29,971
Oh, sure, there were fat ones and skinny ones, tall ones and short ones,

22
00:01:30,081 --> 00:01:33,171
but they all were confused, all were lonesome.

23
00:01:33,361 --> 00:01:37,730
Just a few days before, some of these were rising young executives.

24
00:01:37,921 --> 00:01:42,851
Some were farmers, some were salesmen, drifters, blue-collar workers.

25
00:01:43,041 --> 00:01:49,091
A few days before, they had been many things, but at the induction center, they were all alike.

26
00:01:49,521 --> 00:01:52,691
I figured out something pretty basic back then.

27
00:01:52,961 --> 00:01:58,131
I discovered people are alike in many, many more ways than they are different.

28
00:01:58,321 --> 00:02:01,651
I discovered the other fellow is pretty much like me.

29
00:02:01,760 --> 00:02:06,770
He likes good food, he misses his family and friends, he wants to get ahead,

30
00:02:06,881 --> 00:02:09,571
he has problems, he likes to relax.

31
00:02:09,760 --> 00:02:15,171
So if the other fellow is basically like me, there's no point in being afraid of him.

32
00:02:16,240 --> 00:02:18,530
Now, doesn't that make sense?

33
00:02:18,721 --> 00:02:24,131
If the other fellow is basically like me, there's no reason to be afraid of him.

34
00:02:25,681 --> 00:02:29,411
Here are two ways to put people in proper perspective.

